metadata.name: [ranges] #104
metadata.description: [ranges] is a generative series of digital mountains connected by programatic features with similarity in form, structure, and alignment that have arisen from the same cause. [ranges] are usually segmented by [uplifted_blocks] or [thrust_sheets]. Individual mountains within the same mountain range do not necessarily have the same [plate_tectonics]. They may be a mix of different [orogeny] expressions and [climate].

metadata.name: Framed Flowers #48
metadata.description:
A geometrical flower displayed in a colorfull frame. Or the opposite.

Variations include :
- 10 different color palettes
- Light or dark background
- Rare « negative » mode
- Aerial, Diamond, Round, Squared frames in various combinations
- 8 types of flower shapes, with various modifiers, some duality
- And much more ! 

Play with the variation feature to check various options.

metadata.name: Composition #3 Patchwork Quilt #30
metadata.description:
Abstract, non-square(!) composition based on textural strokes and noise. There are a lot of possible combinations with all of the features! 50% chance of two different palette sets. 50% chance to have a brush textured background, and a 50% chance of it being horizontal or vertical. The quadtree rectangles are based on poisson disc sampling based on a simplex noise field. 90% of the compositions will be smaller boxes, and 10% will be large. For each box, there is a 10% chance that it will be oriented opposite of the rest.

Press ’s’ to save a screenshot.

metadata.name: Prelude to a Civilization #8
metadata.description:
This collection is inspired by Victor Brauner’s 1954 painting, Prelude to a Civilization. I saw it at the Met’s Surrealism Beyond Borders exhibition this summer. I also adore the child- and dream-like quality of the work of Paul Klee.

What’s a better way to combine all these elements with a Klee-inspired palette, Brauner-inspired layout, and Google’s Quick, Draw! doodle dataset?

I never got a chance as a kid to play and doodle. I studied math and spent way too much time on the computer. But maybe this is all coming in full circle? Maybe, we are creating some new civilization in the generative art space?

I hope this brings you a smile and nostalgia for that little kid. Naive maybe, but wide-eyed and full of wonder and hope.

(This is a relatively rare hat tip to SMOLSKULL.)

metadata.name: Perpetual Mayan Calendar #30
metadata.description:
Each calendar is unique, lines and curves entangled with motion geometry and symetry.
Initially, it runs in one shot mode, but you can interact with it : 
- press 'p' anytime to pause
- press 'c' to clear and redraw
- press 'e' to enable endless loop
- press 'm' a few times and ... you'll see

metadata.name: Lakeside #93
metadata.description:
A random lakeside landscape.
Varies in weather, wind-strength, skycolor and more.
Day/Night cycle based on your local system-time. Click/Tap for day/night change.

Open Live-View and hit 's' to save a high-res image of the current state.
Manual resolution toggle with 'd'.
Manual lake-blurring toggle with 'b'.

- @TeNinEightNFTs

Created with p5.js, p5.createloop and p5.collide2d.

metadata.name: waves #81
metadata.description: I was born in Hawaii, and my thoughts often go back to that place. There is a beach on the North shore of Kauai where, at certain times of the year and sea conditions, the sunset lights up the tubes of the waves with spectacular colors, and if you're inside the tube you see an amazing light show. I've many times thought of trying to take advantage of this phenomenon with long exposure photographs and colored LEDs. This p5.js sketch is an attempt to relate with code what I see in my head for that real-world process.
